Description:
If I write
#!/bin/bash
echo "foo"
or
#!/bin/sh
echo "foo"
both yields same. I have seen some scripts starting with
#!/bin/sh
or
#!/bin/bash
. Is there any difference between them?

In Nautilus, when you double click a file, it will open it with the default application associated with the file's extension. For instance, .html files will open in a web browser and .pdf will be opened with Document Viewer. Is there a way to reproduce the same behavior from within the command line (i.e.
open path/filename
)? I'm asking because I like to browse my file-system from the command line but sometimes don't remember which app. opens what.
